Bind mounts, host paths into containers.

A bind mount maps a path on your host directly into a container. There is no docker-managed storage and no copying. The container simply sees the host's bytes. So you might bind-mount a folder of website files from your home directory into a web server's document root, read-only, and then editing a file on the host and refreshing the browser shows the change instantly. Making the mount read-only is a good default whenever the container has no business writing back to your source.

This is the local-development workhorse. The pattern is to keep your source code on the host, where your editor and git live, run the app inside a container with that source bind-mounted, and either restart the container on each change or use a hot-reloading runtime. The trade-off is that bind mounts hardcode the host path, so the same command will not work on a teammate's machine unless their paths match. That is precisely why production deploys use volumes and compose files use relative paths that resolve against the project root.

A few gotchas come with bind mounts. Unlike a volume, a bind mount silently masks whatever was at the container path, with no image-content copy. The host path must exist, and on linux docker will helpfully create an empty directory if it does not, which is almost never what you wanted, so a typo gives you a mysteriously empty container. Permissions can confuse you, because the container sees the host's numeric user and group I-Ds literally. And on mac and windows, where docker has to bridge host filesystem events into a linux virtual machine, bind-mounting a large directory like a dependency folder with hundreds of thousands of files can be brutally slow, which we deal with later.
